<DOC><DOCNO> AP900126-0127 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-90 1633EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Crash     01-26 0231</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Crash,0238</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Fighter Jet Crashes; Search For Pilot</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A U.S. Marine Corps Harrier support fighter jetcrashed Friday off Okinawa and a search has begun for its pilot,the U.S. military announced.   The one-seat AV-8B Harrier aircraft was flying from Kadena AirBase on Okinawa Island to Osan Air Base in South Korea when it wentdown, according to the United States Forces, Japan.   A search is under way for the pilot, whose name was withheldpending notification of relatives, the military said.   Three Japanese coast guard patrol ships and a helicopter weresent to the scene near Iheijima Island, about 88 miles northeast ofNaha, Okinawa, said a night duty officer of the Japan MaritimeSafety Agency.   The Japanese coast guard officer said the aircraft, which wasflying in formation with another Harrier, crashed 23 milesnortheast of Iheijima.   The U.S. military said the USS St. Louis was diverted to thearea to help in the search.   Herbert Nakayoshi, a spokesman for the Marine Corps on Okinawa,said the Marines' Harriers in Japan are based in Iwakuni, insouthwestern Japan, but regularly operate out of Kadena Air Base.   The plane that crashed was assigned to Marine Attack Squadron542 and based at Iwakuni on a six-month deployment program. Thesquadron's home base is at Cherry Point, N.C.   The cause of the accident is under investigation.</TEXT></DOC>